EXECUTIVE SUMMARY: THE MOMENT IS NOW

1.0 The Strategic Imperative

Humanity stands at an inflection point in space exploration. The International Space Station has demonstrated sustained human presence in Low Earth Orbit. Artemis is returning humans to the Moon. The next logical, necessary, and achievable step is sustainable human exploration of Mars and beyond.

The Interplanetary Transport Vehicle (ITV) represents the missing infrastructure to make this possible: not a destination spacecraft, but a reusable interplanetary ferry that cycles between planetary orbits, supporting multiple missions over decades of service.

2.0 Core Innovation: The Cycling Orbital Architecture

Unlike traditional "throw-away" Mars mission concepts, the ITV employs a revolutionary but practical architecture:

1. NEVER LANDS ON PLANETS – Eliminates massive entry/descent/ascent systems
2. REUSABLE ACROSS MULTIPLE MISSIONS – 20-year design life with periodic upgrades
3. MODULAR & EVOLVABLE – Can be incrementally assembled and improved
4. ALWAYS HAS A CREW RETURN VEHICLE ATTACHED – Non-negotiable safety requirement

3.0 The Three-Path Strategy: Mitigating All Major Risks

Path Technology Focus First Major Mission Fallback Position
PATH A Solar-Electric Power 2038 Venus Flyby Limited to inner Solar System
PATH B Nuclear-Electric Power 2042 Mars Orbital Requires political approvals
PATH C Advanced Cryogenics All missions Hypergolic propulsion backup

4.0 The "Apollo 8 Moment": Venus Flyby 2038

Before Mars, we propose an achievable, transformative milestone: A human crew flying by Venus in 2038. This 1.5-year mission:

· Validates 90% of Mars mission systems
· Delivers monumental science returns
· Captures global public imagination
· Costs <$20B through international partnership
· Uses only existing or near-term launch vehicles

5.0 International Consortium Model

Learning from ISS success, we propose an ITV Consortium with:

· Clear governance based on contribution shares
· Cross-waiver of liability among partners
· Tiered technology sharing protocols
· Independent safety oversight board

6.0 Bottom Line: Why This Works Now

1. TECHNOLOGY READINESS: All critical technologies reach TRL 6+ by 2030
2. LAUNCH CAPABILITY: Starship/SLS/New Glenn enable orbital assembly
3. POLITICAL WILL: Multiple nations seek post-ISS leadership
4. COMMERCIAL INTEREST: $2T+ space economy projected by 2040
5. PUBLIC SUPPORT: Mars remains compelling public objective

---

PART I: ARCHITECTURAL VISION & RATIONALE

1.1 The Problem with Traditional Mars Architectures

Current Mars mission designs suffer from fundamental flaws:

· Massive Single-Use Systems: Apollo-style "throw everything away" approach at Mars-scale costs
· Radiation Exposure: 900+ mSv doses without dedicated shielding
· Zero Abort Options: No return capability after certain mission phases
· No Reusability: Each mission requires building everything anew
· Limited Science: Brief surface stays with minimal infrastructure

1.2 The ITV Solution: A Paradigm Shift

The ITV transforms interplanetary travel from episodic expeditions to sustainable transportation infrastructure:

```
Earth System:          [Gateway] <--> [ITV] <--> [Mars System]
                        Crew/Cargo     Cycling     Crew/Cargo
                        Transfer       Transport    Transfer
```

1.3 Guiding Design Principles

1. SAFETY FIRST: Crew survival guaranteed through multiple redundant systems
2. EVOLVABILITY: Design for 20-year service life with block upgrades
3. INTERNATIONALITY: Built-in partnership from requirements phase
4. AFFORDABILITY: Cost per mission decreases with reuse
5. SCIENCE ENABLING: Primary goal is facilitating discovery

1.4 Comparative Advantage Over Existing Concepts

Aspect NASA Mars DRA 5.0 SpaceX Starship ITV Architecture
Reusability Minimal Full Full orbital vehicle
Radiation Protection Limited Minimal Comprehensive (25 g/cm²)
Abort Options Limited windows None after TMI Always-available CRV
International Role NASA-led Commercial Consortium-built
First Crew Mission ~2040 ~2030s 2038 (Venus), 2044 (Mars)

