PART II: TECHNICAL ARCHITECTURE

2.1 Vehicle Configuration & Mass Budget

2.1.1 Three Primary Configurations

CONFIGURATION 1: STARTER ITV (Venus Flyby)

```
Dry Mass: 235 metric tons
Propellant: 195 tons (180 chemical + 15 electric)
Total LEO Mass: 430 tons
Crew: 4
Duration: 1.5 years
Power: 150 kW solar arrays
Propulsion: Methalox chemical + Hall-effect electric
```

CONFIGURATION 2: MARS ITV - SOLAR

```
Dry Mass: 340 metric tons
Propellant: 270 tons (250 chemical + 20 electric)
Total LEO Mass: 610 tons
Crew: 6
Duration: 3 years
Power: 300 kW solar arrays
Propulsion: Methalox chemical + 300kW Hall-effect
Payload to Mars Orbit: 50 tons
```

CONFIGURATION 3: MARS ITV - NUCLEAR

```
Dry Mass: 385 metric tons
Propellant: 280 tons (250 chemical + 30 electric)
Total LEO Mass: 665 tons
Crew: 6
Duration: 3 years
Power: 1 MWe fission reactor
Propulsion: Methalox chemical + Nuclear Electric Propulsion
Payload to Mars Orbit: 60 tons
```

2.1.2 Mass Breakdown (Mars Solar Configuration Example)

Subsystem Mass (tons) % of Dry Mass Key Components
Structure 75 22% Primary spine, docking interfaces, MMOD shielding
Habitation 60 18% Crew quarters, galley, hygiene, common areas
Life Support 30 9% ECLSS, water/waste, atmosphere management
Radiation Protection 30 9% Water walls, polyethylene, storm shelter
Power System 35 10% Solar arrays, batteries, distribution
Propulsion 75 22% Chemical stage, electric stage, RCS
Avionics & Control 15 4% Computers, navigation, communications
Crew Return Vehicle 20 6% Orion-derived capsule with 30-day endurance
TOTAL DRY MASS 340 100% 

2.2 Structural Architecture

2.2.1 Spine-and-Module Design

PRIMARY SPINE:

· Length: 40 meters
· Diameter: 8 meters
· Construction: 3D-printed titanium lattice with composite skin
· Functions: Primary load path, utility routing (power/data/fluids), module attachment

MODULE ATTACHMENT SYSTEM:

· Standardized interface ring (5m diameter)
· 6 attachment points along spine
· Each module electrically, thermally, and fluidly independent
· Quick-disconnect for emergency jettison

2.2.2 Micrometeoroid & Orbital Debris Protection

MULTI-LAYER SHIELD SYSTEM:

1. Outer Bumper: 2mm aluminum (sacrificial layer)
2. Spacing: 30cm vacuum gap
3. Intermediate: Nextel/Kevlar blanket (10 layers)
4. Inner Wall: 4mm aluminum pressure hull
5. Spall Liner: Vectran fabric interior layer

PERFORMANCE: Withstands impacts up to 1cm diameter at 15 km/s

2.2.3 Radiation Protection Strategy

PASSIVE SHIELDING:

· Habitation Zone: Minimum 25 g/cm² hydrogenous shielding
· Water Walls: Processed water, wastewater, and fuel tanks arranged as shielding
· Storm Shelter: 50 g/cm² protection in dedicated 10m³ compartment
· Materials: Polyethylene, lithium hydride, water, methane fuel

ACTIVE COUNTERMEASURES:

· Real-time radiation monitoring (6 dosimeter arrays)
· Solar storm early warning (30-60 minute advance notice)
· Automated crew relocation to storm shelter

DOSE ANALYSIS (Mars Mission):

· Galactic Cosmic Rays: 400 mSv (with shielding)
· Solar Particle Events: 120 mSv (with storm shelter use)
· TOTAL MISSION DOSE: 520 mSv (Below 600 mSv career limit)

2.3 Propulsion Systems

2.3.1 Hybrid Propulsion Philosophy

CHEMICAL STAGE: For high-thrust maneuvers

· Trans-Mars/TMI Injection
· Mars Orbit Insertion
· Emergency abort maneuvers
· Propellant: Methane/LOX (methalox)
· Engines: 4× 250 kN thrust, throttleable, restartable
· ISP: 370 seconds (vacuum)
· Propellant mass: 250 tons (Mars mission)

ELECTRIC PROPULSION: For efficient transit

· Interplanetary cruise (90% of ΔV)
· Station keeping
· Trajectory corrections
· Propellant: Krypton (for Hall thrusters)
· Thrusters: 6× 100 kW Hall-effect
· ISP: 2,500 seconds
· Propellant mass: 20 tons (Mars mission)

2.3.2 Nuclear Electric Propulsion Option

REACTOR SPECIFICATIONS (Path B):

· Type: Fast spectrum, heat pipe cooled
· Power: 1 MWe electrical (2.5 MW thermal)
· Mass: 15 tons (reactor + shield)
· Fuel: HALEU (High-Assay Low-Enriched Uranium, <20% U-235)
· Lifetime: 15 years

PROPULSION ADVANTAGES:

· Transit time reduction: 180 → 120 days (Earth-Mars)
· Higher power for science instruments
· Unlimited operation in Mars shadow

2.3.3 Cryogenic Fluid Management

ZERO-BOIL-OFF REQUIREMENTS:

· Methane storage: 5 years with <1% loss
· LOX storage: 5 years with <0.5% loss
· LH2 storage (nuclear option): 3 years with <5% loss

TECHNOLOGY STACK:

1. Multi-layer Insulation: 80 layers with reflective shields
2. Active Cooling: Stirling cryocoolers (10K lift)
3. Vapor Cooling: Boil-off used to cool shield layers
4. Para-Ortho Hydrogen Conversion: For LH2 storage

FALLBACK POSITION: If ZBO not achieved by 2032, switch chemical stage to storable hypergolics (NTO/MMH)

2.4 Life Support & Habitability

2.4.1 Environmental Control & Life Support System

ATMOSPHERE MANAGEMENT:

· Pressure: 101.3 kPa (Earth sea level)
· Composition: 79% N₂, 21% O₂, <1% CO₂
· Temperature: 22°C ± 2°C
· Humidity: 40-60% RH

CLOSED-LOOP PERFORMANCE TARGETS:

· Oxygen recovery: >95%
· Water recovery: >90%
· CO₂ reduction: >95%

SYSTEM COMPONENTS:

1. CO₂ Removal: 4-Bed Molecular Sieve (4BMS)
2. CO₂ Reduction: Sabatier reactor (CO₂ + H₂ → CH₄ + H₂O)
3. Oxygen Generation: Water electrolysis (Nafion membrane)
4. Trace Contaminant Control: Activated charcoal + catalytic oxidation
5. Water Recovery: Vapor Compression Distillation + RO + UV

2.4.2 Food Systems

PHASED APPROACH:

· Mission 1-3: 85% packaged food, 15% fresh (salads, herbs)
· Mission 4+: 70% packaged, 20% fresh, 10% bioregenerative

VEGETABLE PRODUCTION SYSTEM:

· Type: LED-lit aeroponics
· Area: 20m² (per 6 crew)
· Yield: 5kg fresh vegetables per day
· Crops: Lettuce, kale, tomatoes, peppers, herbs
· Psychological benefit: Rated "high" by astronaut surveys

2.4.3 Artificial Gravity & Exercise

SHORT-RADIUS CENTRIFUGE:

· Radius: 4 meters
· Rotation rate: 10 RPM
· Gravity level: 0.4g at feet, 0.25g at head
· Usage: 2 hours/day per crew member
· Benefits: Maintains bone density, cardiovascular health

EXERCISE COMPLEMENT:

· Advanced Resistive Exercise Device (ARED)
· Treadmill with vertical loading
· Cycle ergometer
· Requirement: 2.5 hours exercise/day

2.4.4 Human Factors Design

INTERIOR ARCHITECTURE PRINCIPLES:

1. Visual Variety: Different textures, colors, lighting in each zone
2. Acoustic Control: <50 dBA in sleeping quarters
3. Privacy: Individual 4m³ sleeping quarters
4. Community: 20m² common area with viewports
5. Operational Efficiency: Everything within reach, intuitive interfaces

LIGHTING SYSTEM:

· Tunable white LEDs (2700K-6500K)
· Circadian rhythm programming
· Sunrise/sunset simulation
· Emergency red lighting

2.5 Avionics, Control & Navigation

2.5.1 Computing Architecture

TRIPLE-MODULAR REDUNDANCY:

· 3 independent computing lanes
· Voting system for critical decisions
· Each lane: 3× radiation-hardened processors
· Memory: ECC-protected, scrubbed every 24 hours

ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE LAYERS:

1. Diagnostic AI: Continuous system health monitoring
2. Planning AI: Mission timeline optimization
3. Interface AI: Natural language crew interaction
4. Security AI: Anomaly detection and response

CYBERSECURITY:

· Air-gapped critical systems
· Quantum-resistant cryptography (Lattice-based)
· Continuous penetration testing
· Hardware security modules

2.5.2 Navigation Systems

PRIMARY (EARTH-RELATIVE):

· X-band Doppler ranging (DSN)
· Accuracy: <50 meters at Mars distance
· Latency: Up to 20 minutes (one-way)

SECONDARY (AUTONOMOUS):

· Optical navigation camera
· Star tracker (0.5 arcsecond accuracy)
· Lidar for proximity operations
· Cold atom interferometer (experimental)

CONTINGENCY:

· Pulsar navigation (X-ray detector)
· Catalog of 50 millisecond pulsars
· Position accuracy: <100 km autonomous

2.5.3 Communications

DATA RATES (MARS AT OPPOSITION):

· Ka-band to DSN: 10 Mbps
· Laser comm (to relay satellite): 100 Mbps
· Emergency S-band: 1 kbps

NETWORK ARCHITECTURE:

· Interplanetary Internet Protocol (Bundle Protocol)
· Delay-Tolerant Networking
· Automatic store-and-forward
· Priority queuing for critical data

2.6 Power Systems

2.6.1 Solar Option (Path A)

ARRAY DESIGN:

· Type: Roll-out solar arrays (ROSA)
· Efficiency: 34% (multi-junction InGaP/GaAs/InGaAs)
· Area: 800m² total (4×200m² wings)
· Power: 300 kW at Mars (600 kW at Earth)
· Degradation: <10% over 10 years

ENERGY STORAGE:

· Lithium-ion batteries: 200 kWh (peak loads)
· Regenerative fuel cells: 500 kWh (eclipse periods)
· Flywheels: 50 kWh (attitude control coupling)

2.6.2 Nuclear Option (Path B)

REACTOR DESIGN:

· Name: "Prometheus-2" (evolved from Kilopower)
· Type: Fast spectrum, Stirling conversion
· Electrical output: 1 MWe
· Thermal output: 2.5 MWt
· Shield: Lithium hydride + tungsten
· Mass: 15 tons (reactor + shield + radiators)

SAFETY FEATURES:

· Sub-critical during launch
· Multiple independent shutdown systems
· Intact re-entry survival (if possible)
· 500-year orbit lifetime if stranded

2.6.3 Power Distribution

ARCHITECTURE:

· Voltage: 400V DC primary bus
· Fault tolerance: Single-fault tolerant
· Reconfiguration: Software-defined within 100ms
· Efficiency: >95% end-to-end

2.7 Crew Return Vehicle

2.7.1 Design Specifications

BASELINE: ORION-DERIVED CAPSULE

· Crew: 6 + 1 rescue capacity
· Endurance: 30 days autonomous
· Launch mass: 20 tons
· Heat shield: Avcoat ablator (10cm thickness)
· Parachutes: 3 main chutes (2-out-of-3)
· Landing: Ocean splashdown (primary), land backup

KEY MODIFICATIONS FROM ORION:

· Extended consumables (30 vs 21 days)
· Enhanced radiation shielding
· Docking adapter for ITV spine
· External service ports for docked maintenance

2.7.2 Emergency Scenarios

IMMEDIATE ABORT (WITHIN 1 HOUR):

· Cause: ITV imminent destruction
· Action: CRV separates, executes escape burn
· Destination: Earth direct entry or safe orbit

CONTINGENCY RETURN (WITHIN 30 DAYS):

· Cause: ITV disabled but stable
· Action: Crew transfers to CRV, plans return
· Options: Wait for rescue, execute slow return

2.8 Thermal Control

HEAT REJECTION SYSTEM:

· Radiators: Deployable, variable conductance
· Area: 150m² total
· Temperature range: -40°C to +50°C
· Fluids: Ammonia primary, water secondary

INTERNAL THERMAL MANAGEMENT:

· Cold plates for electronics
· Air-to-liquid heat exchangers
· Zoned temperature control
· Waste heat utilization (water heating)

