PART III: PROGRAMMATIC FRAMEWORK

3.1 International Consortium Model

3.1.1 Governance Structure

ITV GOVERNING BOARD:

· 15 members (5 NASA, 4 ESA, 2 JAXA, 2 CSA, 2 Industry)
· Decisions: 2/3 majority for technical, 3/4 for budgetary
· Meetings: Quarterly in-person, monthly virtual

TECHNICAL AUTHORITY:

· Independent Verification & Validation team
· Authority to stop work for safety concerns
· Reports directly to Governing Board

3.1.2 Contribution Framework

CONTRIBUTION CLASSES:

1. CLASS A (20%+ share): NASA, ESA
   · Rights: Board seats, technology access, crew slots
   · Responsibilities: Major funding, critical systems
2. CLASS B (5-20% share): JAXA, CSA, major nations
   · Rights: Limited board seats, some technology
   · Responsibilities: Module development, operations
3. CLASS C (<5% share): Other nations, universities
   · Rights: Science participation, data access
   · Responsibilities: Funding, ground support

3.1.3 Liability & Legal Framework

CROSS-WAIVER OF LIABILITY:

· Partners waive claims against each other
· Covers damage to ITV, crew injury, third-party damage
· Exceptions: Willful misconduct, IP claims

CREW PROVISIONS:

· Status: "International astronauts" under treaty
· Medical care: Provided by sending agency
· Compensation: Standardized across partners

3.2 Development Phasing

3.2.1 Phase 0: Foundation & Decision (2026-2030)

BUDGET: $3B total ($600M/year)

· 2026: Consortium formation, requirements definition
· 2027: Three parallel architecture studies
· 2028: Technology down-select (Nuclear vs Solar)
· 2029: Preliminary Design Review (PDR)-level designs
· 2030: Phase 0 Final Review: Go/No-Go for full development

DECISION GATES:

1. Gate 1 (2028): Cryogenic storage TRL 7 achieved?
2. Gate 2 (2029): International funding commitments secured?
3. Gate 3 (2030): Launch vehicle availability confirmed?

3.2.2 Phase 1: Starter ITV (2031-2038)

BUDGET: $18B total ($2.25B/year)

· 2031-2033: Detailed design, component development
· 2034-2036: Manufacturing, ground testing
· 2037: Orbital assembly (5 heavy launches)
· 2038: Crewed Venus Flyby Mission (1.5 years)

KEY MILESTONES:

· 2035: First spine module launch
· 2036: Habitation module launch & mating
· 2037: Full vehicle checkout in LEO
· 2038 Q1: Crew launch and mission start

3.2.3 Phase 2: Mars ITV (2039-2044)

BUDGET: $25B total ($4.2B/year)

· 2039-2041: Mars-configuration upgrades
· 2042: Uncrewed Mars orbital shakedown
· 2043: Lander development complete
· 2044: First crewed Mars orbital mission

3.3 Cost Sharing Model

TOTAL PROGRAM COST: $46B (2025 dollars)

· Phase 0: $3B (6.5%)
· Phase 1: $18B (39%)
· Phase 2: $25B (54%)

SAMPLE CONTRIBUTION ALLOCATION:

· NASA: $18B (39%) - Core vehicle, CRV, operations
· ESA: $12B (26%) - Habitation, electric propulsion
· JAXA: $6B (13%) - Life support, robotics
· CSA: $4B (9%) - Manipulators, interfaces
· Other Partners: $6B (13%) - Science, subsystems

3.4 Industrial Participation

PRIME CONTRACTORS:

· Vehicle Integration: Boeing/Airbus joint venture
· Propulsion: Aerojet Rocketdyne + European consortium
· Habitation: Thales Alenia Space
· Life Support: JAXA-led team
· Avionics: Honeywell + European suppliers

SMALL BUSINESS SET-ASIDE: 20% of contracts to companies <500 employees
EMERGING SPACE INCENTIVE:15% bonus for commercial partners using own funding

3.5 Risk Management

3.5.1 Top 5 Program Risks

Risk Probability Impact Mitigation
1. Cryo Storage Failure Medium High Hypergolic fallback; aggressive tech demo
2. Nuclear Approval Delay High Medium Solar baseline; phased approval approach
3. Launch Vehicle Delays Medium High Multiple providers; on-orbit storage
4. International Withdrawal Low High Core group of 4 agencies; bilateral backups
5. Radiation Overexposure Low High Conservative design; continuous monitoring

3.5.2 Technology Readiness Timeline

TRL 6 BY 2028:

· Methalox engines (Starship heritage)
· Hall-effect thrusters (300kW class)
· Solar arrays (35% efficiency)
· Closed-loop life support (90% water)

TRL 6 BY 2030:

· Zero-boil-off cryogenics
· Space fission power (1 MWe)
· Artificial gravity centrifuge
· Optical interplanetary comms

3.6 Science Integration

3.6.1 Primary Research Themes

1. MARS SYSTEM SCIENCE:
   · Atmospheric evolution
   · Subsurface water mapping
   · Phobos/Deimos origins
   · Current habitability
2. FUNDAMENTAL PHYSICS:
   · Gravitational wave detection
   · Dark matter searches
   · Quantum mechanics tests
   · Relativity verification
3. ASTROBIOLOGY:
   · Life detection experiments
   · Planetary protection studies
   · Prebiotic chemistry

3.6.2 Science Payload Allocation

MARS MISSION:

· Internal labs: 10 tons
· External instruments: 5 tons
· Deployable platforms: 5 tons
· Sample return capacity: 1 ton

CREW TIME ALLOCATION:

· Science operations: 40 hours/week
· Vehicle maintenance: 30 hours/week
· Exercise/health: 20 hours/week
· Personal time: 30 hours/week

