PART IV: ROADMAP TO IMPLEMENTATION

4.1 Near-Term Actions (2026-2027)

4.1.1 2026: Foundation Year

Q1-Q2 2026:

· Distribute this white paper to space agencies
· Secure "expressions of interest" from 6+ nations
· Establish interim steering committee

Q3 2026:

· FIRST ITV SUMMIT (Geneva, October 2026)
  · 200 participants from agencies, industry, science
  · Formal announcement of consortium intent
  · Establishment of three study teams

Q4 2026:

· Release draft consortium agreement
· Begin Phase 0 funding allocations
· Kick off parallel architecture studies

4.1.2 2027: Definition Year

PARALLEL STUDIES:

1. TEAM SOLAR (NASA-led): Complete 90-day Venus flyby mission design
2. TEAM NUCLEAR (ESA-led): Nuclear safety/approval pathway
3. TEAM CRYOGENIC (JAXA-led): ZBO technology demonstration plan

MID-YEAR MILESTONE:

· Preliminary Requirements Review (PRR)
· Down-select to 2 power system options
· Finalize crew size (4 for Venus, 6 for Mars)

4.2 Technology Development Timeline

4.2.1 Ground Demonstrations (2027-2032)

CRYOGENIC STORAGE DEMO:

· 2027: Begin 1-year ZBO ground test
· 2029: Complete 2-year test with methane/LOX
· 2031: Flight-like system TRL 6 achieved

NUCLEAR POWER DEMO:

· 2028: 100 kWe reactor ground test (full power)
· 2030: 1 MWe design complete, safety reviews
· 2032: Flight unit manufacturing begins

LIFE SUPPORT DEMO:

· 2027-2029: HERA analog mission (4 crew, 1 year)
· 2030-2031: Antarctic winter-over test
· 2032: ECLSS TRL 7 achieved

4.2.2 Flight Demonstrators (2033-2036)

DEMO 1: CRYOGENIC DEPOT (2034)

· Launch: Single heavy-lift vehicle
· Duration: 2 years in LEO
· Goal: <1% boil-off per year validated

DEMO 2: HABITATION MODULE (2035)

· Launch: To Lunar Gateway or free-flyer
· Duration: 6-month crewed shakedown
· Goal: Validate closed-loop systems

DEMO 3: ELECTRIC PROPULSION (2036)

· Launch: SEP tug with 10-ton payload
· Mission: Lunar orbit to Earth-Moon L2
· Goal: Validate 300kW Hall thruster operation

4.3 Vehicle Assembly Sequence

4.3.1 Starter ITV Assembly (2037)

LAUNCH MANIFEST:

1. Launch 1: Structural spine (80 tons)
2. Launch 2: Power system + radiators (70 tons)
3. Launch 3: Habitation module (60 tons)
4. Launch 4: Propulsion stage (75 tons)
5. Launch 5: Consumables + CRV (45 tons)
6. Launch 6-8: Propellant (3× 60 tons methalox)
7. Launch 9: Crew (4 via crew vehicle)

ASSEMBLY TIMELINE:

· Month 1-3: Spine checkout, power deployment
· Month 4-6: Module mating, systems integration
· Month 7-9: Propulsion checkout, tanking
· Month 10-12: Crew arrival, final shakedown

4.4 Mission Profiles

4.4.1 Venus Flyby Mission (2038)

OUTBOUND (6 MONTHS):

· Departure: January 2038
· Trajectory: Type IV Venus flyby
· Electric propulsion: Continuous, 0.02g acceleration
· Venus closest approach: 300 km, July 2038
· Science: 48-hour intensive observation period

RETURN (9 MONTHS):

· Post-Venus trajectory adjustment
· Electric propulsion continues
· Earth return: October 2039
· Direct entry via CRV at 13.5 km/s

SCIENCE HIGHLIGHTS:

· Venus atmospheric probes (10×)
· Solar corona observations (during flyby)
· Gravitational lensing experiment
· Deep space radiation mapping

4.4.2 Mars Orbital Mission (2044)

OUTBOUND TRANSIT (180 DAYS):

· Departure: January 2044 (optimal window)
· Chemical burn: 30 minutes (TMI)
· Electric propulsion: 150 days continuous
· Mars arrival: July 2044

MARS ORBIT OPERATIONS (400 DAYS):

· Science: Phobos/Deimos visits (robotic & crewed)
· Surface support: Teleoperation of rovers
· Lander operations: 3 surface sorties (30 days each)
· Crew rotation: 6 crew continuous, with lander teams

EARTH RETURN (210 DAYS):

· Departure: August 2045
· Electric propulsion return
· Earth arrival: March 2046

4.5 Long-Term Evolution

4.5.1 Block Upgrades

BLOCK 1 (2038-2045):

· Venus flyby capability
· Basic Mars orbital support
· 90% closed-loop life support

BLOCK 2 (2046-2055):

· Enhanced radiation shielding
· Nuclear electric propulsion
· 95% closed-loop life support
· Artificial gravity habitat

BLOCK 3 (2056-2065):

· Fully closed biosphere
· Advanced composite structure
· Autonomous robotic servants
· In-situ manufacturing

4.5.2 Extended Missions

ASTEROID BELT (2050s):

· Ceres rendezvous mission (4 years)
· Multiple NEO visits
· Mining technology demonstration

JUPITER SYSTEM (2060s):

· Callisto base support
· Europa sub-surface ocean access
· Ganymede magnetic field studies

